# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-w-schwartz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] He received his AB in Zoology from the University of Missouri in 1938.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] A graduate assistantship during his MA led Schwartz to work with Elizabeth Reeder, a Ph.D. candidate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] They married in 1938 and later had three children.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] In 1940, Schwartz completed his MA and began work at the Missouri Conservation Commission as a biologist.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Schwartz's career with the Missouri Department of Conservation lasted for thirty-nine years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] A short stint from 1946 to 1947 was spent in Hawaii studying wildlife conditions for Hawaii's Board of Agriculture and Forestry.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Throughout the late twentieth century, the Schwartzes wrote and illustrated books, created films, and made artwork on wildlife and conservation topics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] In 1949, *Game Birds of Hawaii* was published and selected by the Wildlife Society as the best publication in wildlife management and ecology for 1949–1950.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Several other films won awards, including a 1952 CONI Grand Medal for *Bobwhite through the Year* and the American Association for Conservation Information best North American wildlife movie award in 1959 for *Story of the Mourning Dove*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] In 1949, Schwartz illustrated Aldo Leopold's landmark book on conservation, *A Sand County Almanac: And Sketches Here and There*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Another Schwartz collaboration, *The Wild Mammals of Missouri*, was co-published by the University of Missouri Press and the Missouri Department of Conservation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Containing over four hundred illustrations and information about sixty-six species, *Wild Mammals* proved to be one of their most important works.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] The American Association for Conservation Information selected it as the outstanding wildlife book in 1959 and revised editions were published in 1981 and 2001.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] Schwartz's artwork was used for Missouri trout and duck stamps, conservation fundraising for the Conservation Federation of Missouri and other efforts, and books by other Missouri wildlife writers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] From 1965 to 1987, he completed murals for the Missouri Department of Conservation headquarters in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] He remained active as an artist and outdoorsman.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] He died from pancreatic cancer at his home in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/charles-w-schwartz] A posthumous book, *About Mammals and How They Live*, was completed by Libby, published in 1993, and selected by the Wildlife Society for its 1994 Conservation Education Award.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is named after the Coeur d'Alene people, a federally recognized tribe of Native Americans who live along the rivers and lakes of the region, in a territory of 4,000,000 acres (16,000 km2) from eastern Washington to Montana.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Historically, the native peoples were hunter-gatherers who located their villages and camps near food gathering or processing sites and followed the seasonal cycles, practicing subsistence hunting, fishing, and foraging.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city began as a fort town; General William Tecumseh Sherman sited what became known as Fort Sherman on the north shore of Lake Coeur d'Alene in 1878.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Peopling of the town came when miners and prospectors came to the region after gold and silver deposits were found in what would become the Silver Valley and after the Northern Pacific Railroad reached the town in 1883.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the 1890s, two significant miners' uprisings over wages took place in the Coeur d'Alene Mining District leading to the declaration of martial law, with the latter providing a motive for the assassination of a former Idaho governor and subsequently a nationally publicized trial.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The late 19th century discovery of highly prized white pine in the forests of northern Idaho resulted in a timber boom that peaked in the late 1920s and was accompanied by the rapid population growth which led to the incorporation of the city on September 4, 1906.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] After the Great Depression, tourism started to become a major source of development in the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] By the 1980s, tourism became the major driver in the local economy, and, after decades of heavy reliance on logging, the city featured a more balanced economy with manufacturing, retail, and service sectors.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene has grown significantly since the 1990s, in part because of a substantial increase in tourism, encouraged by resorts and recreational activities in the area and outmigration predominantly from other western states.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene Resort and its world-record 3,300-foot floating boardwalk and a 165-acre (0.67 km2) natural area called Tubbs Hill take up a prominent portion of the city's downtown.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Popular parks such as City Park and Beach and McEuen Park are also fixtures of the downtown waterfront.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city has become somewhat of a destination for golfers; there are five courses in the city, including the Coeur d'Alene Resort Golf Course and its unique 14th hole floating green.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene Casino and its Circling Raven Golf Club is located approximately 27 miles (43 km) south and the largest theme park in the Northwestern United States, Silverwood Theme Park, is located approximately twenty miles (30 km) north.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There are also several ski resorts and other recreation areas nearby.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is home to the Museum of North Idaho and North Idaho College, and it has become known for having one of the largest holiday light shows in the United States and hosting a popular Ironman Triathlon event.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is located on the route of Interstate 90 and is served by the Coeur d'Alene Airport as well as the Brooks Seaplane Base by air.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In print media, local issues are covered by the *Coeur d'Alene Press* daily newspaper.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The camps featured conical lodges constructed from poles and mats sewn from tule or animal hides.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene people were hunter-gatherers who practiced subsistence hunting of wild game and fishing during the salmon runs, and then foraging for berries and other edibles along the shores of the region's numerous lakes and rivers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The introduction of the horse around 1760 made hunting and transportation more efficient.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The area was extensively explored by fur trader David Thompson of the North West Company starting in 1807, and in 1809 he established the Kullyspell House trading post on Lake Pend Oreille.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Thompson, who usually used native names to describe the places and people he came across, ascribed the name of "Pointed Hearts" to one of the tribes he traded with and "Pointed Heart Lake" to the lake they lived near.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] This term translates the French *Cœur d'Alêne*, literally meaning "heart of an awl", a name apparently bestowed on the tribe by French-speaking Iroquois who viewed them as shrewd traders.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Oregon boundary dispute (or Oregon question) arose as a result of competing British and American claims to the Pacific Northwest of North America in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The British had trading ties extending from Canada and had started settlements at Fort Vancouver and at Fort Astoria on the Pacific coast near the mouth of the Columbia River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Oregon Treaty of 1846 ended the disputed joint occupation of the area in present-day Idaho when Britain ceded all rights to land south of the 49th parallel to the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In another territorial dispute, the U.S. government through Washington Territory Governor Isaac Stevens began to negotiate treaties that would begin to move the various tribes of the region onto reservation lands to make way for American settlement.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] This angered the Coeur d'Alene, as several treaty re-negotiations continually reduced their tribal lands.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The tribe also perceived the planned construction a military wagon road as a precursor to a land-grab by the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene Reservation is located in Benewah and Kootenai counties south of Coeur d'Alene in communities focused around Worley and Plummer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] With the discovery of gold in the western United States and the establishment of Idaho Territory in 1863, there was an increase in settlers to the region.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] When General William Tecumseh Sherman was commander of the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Army during the Indian Wars and following the defeat of General George Armstrong Custer at the Battle of Little Big Horn, he erected several forts in the west.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] During a tour of the Inland Northwest on his way to Fort Walla Walla on the Mullan Road, he was impressed by the scenery of the area and ordered a fort constructed on the lake in 1877 and gave it the name Fort Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The fort which gave the city its name was established in 1878 and the name of the fort was later changed to Fort Sherman to honor the general.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Miners and prospectors came to the region after gold and silver deposits were found in the Coeur d'Alene Mountains and the Northern Pacific Railroad came to the village in 1883.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The village became the location where ore from the mining district was ferried and transferred to the rail lines from steamboats that traveled down from the Coeur d'Alene River from the Cataldo Mission.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The township was officially incorporated by petition on August 22, 1887.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the 1890s, two significant miners' uprisings took place in the Coeur d'Alene Mining District, where the workers struggled with high risk and low pay.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 1892, the union's discovery of a labor spy in their midst, in the person of Charlie Siringo, a sometime cowboy and Pinkerton agent, resulted in a labor strike that developed into a shooting war between miners and the company in Burke Canyon.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] To restore order to the state of rebellion in Shoshone County, Governor N.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Willey declared martial law and sent federal troops to arrest and detain the union miners, but not before dozens of casualties including six deaths and the destruction of the Frisco Mill.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Six hundred miners were put into "bullpens" without any hearings or formal charges.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Labor disputes between some company mines and the union continued into the next decade.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] A similar labor confrontation in 1899 took place after the union was launching an organizing drive of the few mines not yet fully unionized, where miners working in the Bunker Hill and Sullivan mines were receiving fifty cents to a dollar less per day than other miners.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] With no success in the effort, on April 29, 250 union members seized a train in Burke at gunpoint, according to the engineer, Levi "Al" Hutton.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] At each stop through Burke Canyon, more miners climbed aboard what was dubbed the "Dynamite Express" toward the site of the $250,000 Bunker Hill mine near Wardner; the miners then carried 3,000 pounds (1,400 kg) of dynamite into the mill and completely destroyed it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The crowd also burned down the company office, the boarding house, and the home of the mine manager.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Like in the 1892 strike, martial law was declared by Governor Frank Steunenberg and wholesale arrests and mass incarcerations were done to bring back order.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Harry Orchard, who owned a share of the Hercules Mine at one point and played a significant role in the Colorado Labor Wars, returned to Idaho to assassinate former governor Steunenberg in 1905.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The bombing assassination led to a nationally publicized trial in Boise.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Geological Survey done in the 1890s, it became widely known that there were large quantities of white pine, a highly prized softwood, in the Coeur d'Alene Mountains.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The lumber industry from the eastern US began to inventory the timberlands, acquire land, and invest in facilities across much of northern Idaho.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] This was welcome relief to the town of Coeur d'Alene, which had been reeling from the Panic of 1893, a flood in 1894, and the closure of Fort Sherman.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city experienced significant growth from the timber boom and the development of the railroads, steamboats, and tourism that accompanied it; Coeur d'Alene incorporated as a city on September 4, 1906, and by 1908 it had become the county seat.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] From 1900 to 1915, there were hundreds of homes constructed across 70 newly platted additions.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] After the 1929 stock market crash and during the Great Depression, the lumber industry demand began to wane and by the mid-1930s about half the woodworkers in North Idaho were laid off and the surviving mills were producing only 160 million board feet of lumber per year.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Playfair Pier opened on July 4, 1942 (and existed until 1974) in City Park and included a variety of rides and attractions such as a miniature roller coaster, a Ferris wheel, a carousel, and some of the usual carnival games.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene benefited from its proximity to the Farragut Naval Training Station, established in 1942 on the south end of Lake Pend Oreille, which employed 22,000 people and needed 98 million board feet of lumber to build 650 buildings.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Due to the scenic lake, tourism has always been a factor in the local economy.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the early 1900s, it had become popular in Spokane to travel and picnic in the park, shop in town, and take steamboat cruises on the lake and up the Saint Joe River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene had also received national publicity in magazines, where it had been called a "wonderland" and "the Lucerne of America".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] However, tourism began to become a mainstay of the economy with the completion of highway infrastructure projects in the 1950s and 1960s, and the Coeur d'Alene Chamber of Commerce began to promote the city as a tourist destination as well.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] As tourism increased, there was more demand for lodging facilities, convention space, restaurants, and cultural activities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] By 1976, the city had over 30 motels with about 1,500 rooms.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] On June 14, 1958, the city hosted the first Diamond Cup Hydroplane race, which was one of the largest events in its history and garnered national publicity and media coverage.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The event was attended by 30,000 people, and it was considered a success by the Diamond Cup organizers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The race was held at Lake Coeur d'Alene for the next eight years; it was discontinued due to persistent difficulties in raising funds for the event.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] After decades of heavy reliance on logging, in the 1980s, the city featured a more balanced economy with manufacturing, retail, and service sectors.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Tourism has taken on even more prominence and has become one of the main drivers of the local economy since the start of the 1980s, when there was new investment into recreational tourism in the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 1982, a $2 million Wild Waters aquatic theme park was built, and in the spring of 1986 there was the opening of the $60 million ($176 million in 2025 dollars), 18-story Coeur d'Alene Resort.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The waterfront resort featured a well-manicured frontage and a publicly accessible floating boardwalk that gave visitors the impression of a park-like environment and attracted the attention of publications nationwide.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The actions of the Aryan Nations, a white supremacist group founded by Richard Butler in 1974, also attracted media attention.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Butler's acolytes, many of whom were transplants like him, were linked to several robberies, murders, and three bombings, including the bombing of a *Spokesman-Review* office.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 1986, Coeur d'Alene was presented the Raoul Wallenberg Award for its stand in peacefully countering the message of the white supremacists that moved into the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene also won the All-America City Award in 1990.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Aryan Nations went bankrupt and ceased operations in 2000 when the Southern Poverty Law Center filed a lawsuit after the assault of a Native American woman.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The lawsuit resulted in a $6.3 million judgment and the closure of their Hayden compound.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] A successor group, Jerald O'Brien's Aryan Nations, is still based in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the 1990s, the Coeur d'Alene area starting experiencing substantial population growth; many of these initial transplants came from California, citing earthquakes, crime, and overcrowding as reasons for their move.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] This northward migration coincided with watershed events such as the 1992 Los Angeles riots and the 1994 Northridge earthquake.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The surrounding area got increased tourist attention when Silverwood Theme Park, which opened in 1988 on an airstrip with an authentic steam train and carnival rides, installed the Corkscrew roller coaster in 1990 that it purchased from Knott's Berry Farm.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 2014, McEuen Park on the downtown waterfront reopened to the public after undergoing a major $20 million renovation that transformed it from a park with baseball diamonds into a multi-use park with a variety of athletic facilities, a playground, and a dog park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to Census Bureau data in 2018, the city and county were among the fastest growing metropolitan areas in the nation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The newest transplants are still mainly from other western states and are moving for economic as well as political reasons, seeking a lower cost of living, more affordable housing, an outdoor lifestyle, and a place that is more conservative.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In June 2020, during George Floyd protests, armed civilians patrolled the streets of downtown Coeur d'Alene, citing a desire to protect businesses from potential looting.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In June 2022, 31 members of the hate group Patriot Front, including leader Thomas Rousseau, were arrested after appearing at the city's Pride parade.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The group maintains an active presence in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 2023, the city was noted as a target of American Redoubt-related immigration.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Firefighters responding to a brush fire near Coeur d'Alene on June 29, 2025 were ambushed by a sniper gunfire.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The sniper, 20-year-old Wess Roley, was found dead several hours later.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The fire was thought to have been purposely set to enable the ambush.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 16.08 square miles (41.65 km2), of which 15.57 square miles (40.33 km2) is land and 0.51 square miles (1.32 km2) is water.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is 30 miles (48 km) east of downtown Spokane, Washington, and 259 miles (415 km) east of Seattle.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is part of the Spokane–Coeur d'Alene combined statistical area and the Inland Northwest region, consisting of eastern Washington, northern Idaho, northwestern Montana, and northeastern Oregon.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is located on the north shore of Lake Coeur d'Alene, near the outlet of the Spokane River, and is in the Northern Rockies ecoregion.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Lake Coeur d'Alene is a natural dam-controlled lake that is 25 miles (40 km) long and 1 mile (1.6 km) to 3 miles (4.8 km) wide and fed by the Coeur d'Alene and Saint Joe rivers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Lake in the Spokane Valley and Rathdrum Prairie, were formed by the Missoula Floods, which ended 12,000 to 15,000 years ago.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene Mountains of the Bitterroot Range rise to the east of the city to a maximum elevation of 7,352 feet (2,241 m) at Cherry Peak.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The wooded lands east of the city, the Coeur d'Alene National Forest, have been designated for protection and management by the Idaho Panhandle National Forests.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] These thick forests include groves of ancient western redcedar and host over 300 wildlife species including woodland caribou, Canada lynx, grizzly bear, and northwestern wolf.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The large lakes in the Idaho panhandle attract birds on the Pacific Flyway, and bird watching is popular on Lake Coeur d'Alene, especially from November to February when bald eagles come annually to feed on the spawning kokanee.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Cougar Bay Nature Preserve on the northeast portion of Lake Coeur d'Alene is the closest and most accessible nature preserve for wildlife viewing, as it is located a few minutes from downtown Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Environmental concerns have come as a result of upstream hardrock mining and smelting operations in the Silver Valley.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene Basin, including Lake Coeur d'Alene, is polluted with heavy metals such as lead and was designated a superfund site in 1983 that spans 1,500 square miles (3,884.98 km2) and 166 miles (267 km) of the Coeur d'Alene River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The majority of the lake bed is covered in a layer of contaminated sediment and local health officials at the Panhandle Health District advise the lake's visitors to wash anything that has come into contact with potentially lead-laced soil or dust in the Coeur d'Alene River basin.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene has, depending on the definition, a dry-summer continental climate (Köppen *Dsb*) or a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csb*), characterized by a cold, moist climate in winter, and very warm, dry conditions in summer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The daily mean temperature ranges from 31.2 °F (−0.4 °C) in January and December to 70.1 °F (21.2 °C) in July.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Temperatures exceed 90 °F (32 °C) on 18.3 days per year, only occasionally reaching 100 °F (38 °C), and there may be several nights below 10 °F (−12 °C).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The average first and last freezes of the season are October 17 and April 28, respectively.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city straddles the border between USDA Plant Hardiness Zones 6B and 7A.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Spokane–Coeur d'Alene area has many microclimates that can have different weather patterns and observations from the nearby official reporting stations used by the National Weather Service due to the diversity of the topography and other factors.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] For instance, northern Idaho experiences more precipitation in rain and snow than eastern Washington from weather systems originating from the Pacific Ocean because it is on the windward side of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Average annual rainfall is 25 inches (64 cm) and the average annual snowfall is 46 inches (120 cm).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Northern Idaho weather is influenced by both maritime and continental weather systems.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Moist air masses from the coast are released as precipitation over the North Central Rockies forests, creating the North American inland temperate rainforest, and dry air masses from Canada and the Great Plains contribute to dry summer months.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene can have noticeably milder nights and cooler days due to the moderating effect on the climate of large bodies of water such as Lake Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] As Coeur d'Alene has grown from a fort town, different neighborhoods and suburbs have grown around it.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The downtown city center of Coeur d'Alene is in the southeast of the urban area as the presence of Hayden Lake and Lake Fernan and the Coeur d'Alene mountains inhibit development to the east and Lake Coeur d'Alene and the Spokane River limit development to the south and southwest.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Historic additions from the early 1900s were added close to the city center a few blocks from downtown, such as on East Sherman Avenue, East Lakeshore Drive near Sanders Beach, and near present-day City Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Today, the city has many neighborhoods, the largest being Coeur d'Alene city center, Post Falls and Hayden.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene city center has several parks and attractions and as a community gathering place, it has heavy foot traffic on fair weather summer weekends.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The largest building in the city, the 216-foot (66 m) Coeur d'Alene Resort Lake Tower, is in the city center.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The downtown area is of increasing interest to higher density multifamily apartment and condominium-type developments to cope with the growth in housing demand and due to a lack of space and concerns about urban sprawl.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Investment in residential and retail development has been intensive along the Interstate 90 corridor and has made Post Falls near the Washington state line become Kootenai County's second largest city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Due to its central location between Spokane and Coeur d'Alene, the city is host to a growing list of retail stores and is considered a bedroom community of Spokane.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The historic Post Falls Dam and surrounding Falls Park on the Spokane River is a local landmark.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Hayden is the third largest city in the Coeur d'Alene metropolitan area, and it is known for the eponymous Hayden Lake that was once the historic center of the community.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The shores of the lake are filled with summer cabins and large mansions.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The historic Hayden Lake Country Club, which lies at the center of the Hayden Lake community, was built in 1907 along with a rail connection with the Spokane and Inland Empire Railroad that same year, which brought in many tourists to the resort and Honeysuckle Beach.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] With the rising use of the automobile, the center of town shifted away from the lake and railroad and reoriented toward Government Way.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] As of the 2020 census, Coeur d'Alene had a population of 54,628.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] 22.1% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.8% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] For every 100 females there were 94.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.7 males age 18 and over.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There were 22,754 households in Coeur d'Alene, of which 27.7% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Of all households, 43.4% were married-couple households, 19.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 29.6% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] About 31.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There were 24,206 housing units, of which 6.0% were vacant.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 4.7%.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene and its Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA), which consists of Kootenai County, have been combined by the Census Bureau into the Spokane–Coeur d'Alene Combined Statistical Area (CSA) where it is the third-largest polity after Spokane and its largest suburb, Spokane Valley.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The population of the CSA was 745,213 in 2020.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The principal cities in the CSA are separated by suburbs that largely follow the path of Spokane Valley and Rathdrum Prairie.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The City of Coeur d'Alene has opted not to voluntarily merge with the Spokane MSA and to remain a distinct metropolitan area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to Office of Management and Budget (OMB) guidelines, the two MSAs will automatically be combined by the OMB when the employment interchange exceeds 25 percent; in 2011, 18 percent of residents commuted between Spokane and Kootenai counties for work.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] As of the 2010 census, there were 44,137 people, 18,395 households, and 10,813 families residing in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The population density was 2,834.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,094.5/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There were 20,219 housing units at an average density of 1,298.6 per square mile (501.4/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 93.8% White, 0.4% African American, 1.2% Native American, 0.8% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.9% from other races, and 2.8% from two or more races.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 4.3% of the population.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There were 18,395 households, of which 29.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.2% were married couples living together, 11.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.0% had a male householder with no wife present, and 41.2% were non-families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] 31.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.92.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The median age in the city was 35.4 years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] 22.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.6% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 26.7% were from 25 to 44; 24% were from 45 to 64; and 14.6% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The gender makeup of the city was 48.6% male and 51.4% female.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to the 2010 Metro Area Membership Report of the Association of Religion Data Archives, the denominational affiliations of the Coeur d'Alene MSA (Kootenai County) are 60,657 Evangelical Protestant, 3,064 Mainline Protestant, 7,597 Catholic, 162 Orthodox, 8,492 Other, and 58,522 Unclaimed.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Idaho is part of a region called the Unchurched Belt, a region in the Northwestern United States that has historically low rates of religious participation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The evangelical Christian community has been growing with the overall population and there have been instances of whole congregations moving to the area from out of state.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The evangelical Christian Real Life Ministries church located in Post Falls was the 13th fastest growing church in the nation in 2007.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Many new residents are retirees seeking lower cost of living and traffic; the number of residents aged 65 years and older doubled from 2001 to 2019 according to the Idaho Department of Labor.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to the National Incident-Based Reporting System, the Coeur d'Alene metro area (Kootenai County) crime rate per 100,000 population was 4,864 in 2018, which was lower than the Idaho state average of 5,032.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The county has a property crime rate of 12.88 and a violent crime rate of 1.59 per 1,000 people in the 2018 Uniform Crime Reports summary, which is lower than the Idaho state average of 14.61 and 2.27 respectively.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] According to NeighborhoodScout's methodology, the city has a crime index of 24, meaning it is safer than 24 percent of US cities, and has a property and violent crime rate slightly above the Idaho state average but still below the national median in both categories.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Historically, the economy of Coeur d'Alene was built and based on mining and logging and the Coeur d'Alene Mining District has been one of the world's most productive mining districts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] However, after mining and logging diminished in importance in the 1940s, tourism has come to be the main influence in the local economy ever since.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city has become a major tourist attraction, being at the heart of north Idaho's Lake Country where people partake in water sports and activities such as wake boarding, paddleboarding, sailing, parasailing, jet skiing, kayaking, fishing and other lake recreation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There are three major ski resorts within a short driving distance, Silver Mountain Resort in Kellogg, Lookout Pass Ski and Recreation Area at Lookout Pass near Mullan, and Schweitzer Mountain Ski Resort in Sandpoint.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Tourism and hospitality related jobs employed over 10,000 people in north Idaho in 2010.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is the healthcare, educational, media, manufacturing, retail and recreation center for north Idaho.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene's retail has expanded greatly in recent years with the opening of new stores and entertainment venues; the Silver Lake Mall, which is the largest in North Idaho, was opened in 1989.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene's Village at Riverstone development along Northwest Boulevard houses a park, amphitheater, 14-theater Regal Cinemas, a Hampton Inn, condominiums, restaurants, and local retailers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Companies that have their head offices in Coeur d'Alene include mining company and owner of the Lucky Friday mine in Mullan, Hecla Mining and the U.S. operations of Canada-based restaurant Pita Pit.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] A knife manufacturer, Buck Knives, is the most recognizable brand name in the area, where they relocated the head office and factory from San Diego to the Coeur d'Alene suburb of Post Falls in 2005.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Construction company and roller coaster manufacturer, Rocky Mountain Construction is based in Hayden.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 2017, the Coeur d'Alene metropolitan area had a gross metropolitan product of $5.93 billion.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene metropolitan area has a workforce of 80,000 people and an unemployment rate of 6.8% (as of June 2020); the largest sectors for non-farm employment are trade, transportation, and utilities, government, and education and health services as well as leisure and hospitality.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The average commute to work is 18.5 minutes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Commuting across the state line into Washington is not uncommon.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] A concern for the city is that the rising minimum wage and salary differential between Washington and Idaho will cause local personnel shortages.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In 2011, the Idaho state median hourly wage was $14.51 according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene area has a growing arts scene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The community has a symphony and theater productions from professional and community groups.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city has several art galleries, almost all displaying art located in the walkable downtown area along Sherman Avenue, Coeur d'Alene's main street.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Among the most prominent of these galleries is The Art Spirit Gallery.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Since 1999, the City of Coeur d'Alene has had a funding mechanism for public art where 1.33 percent of the total cost of all eligible above-ground capital improvement projects is earmarked to fund art in public places.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the musical arts, the Coeur d'Alene Symphony traces its roots to the late 1970s as a class at North Idaho College.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The symphony performs an annual free concert for the community on Labor Day in Coeur d'Alene City Park and also performs during the summer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Street artists and musicians frequent Sherman Square performing for pedestrians.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Theater arts are provided by the professional Coeur d'Alene Summer Theatre group and the community theater company, Lake City Playhouse.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city's primary performing arts venues are the Schuler Performing Arts Center within Boswell Hall at North Idaho College and the Kroc Center.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Museum of North Idaho located in downtown Coeur d'Alene chronicles the history of the region.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The museum does walking tours of the Fort Sherman grounds and also rents out the Fort Sherman chapel, the oldest building in the city as a wedding venue.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Many of the community events and activities in Coeur d'Alene occur during the warm summer months and they often take place by the lake.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Annual events include the Fourth of July Festival and the Holiday Light Show that begins at the end of November.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene has been known for hosting big Fourth of July celebrations since its early days as a fort town.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Fourth of July Festival usually includes a parade down Sherman Avenue, food and craft vendors, carnival rides, and live music and entertainment.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Many watch the fireworks by the waterfront and beach; the Coeur d'Alene resort offers fireworks cruises that depart from Independence Point.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In the winter, the Holiday Light Show festivities begin at the end of November and the lights are on display until January 1.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The event also begins with a parade down Sherman Avenue and ends with a fireworks show; the resort's light show features over 1.5 million bulbs, and the resort offers "Journey to the North Pole" cruises.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Another event in the winter months that often gets media attention is the Polar Bear Plunge every year on January 1 at noon, where event participants run into the cold waters of Lake Coeur d'Alene at Sanders Beach.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] One of the most well-attended events in the region combines Art on the Green, the Street Fair, and Taste of Coeur d'Alene, which are all held on the first weekend in August on the North Idaho College campus, downtown Coeur d'Alene, and City Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Art on the Green is an outdoor arts and crafts festival, Street Fair is a shopping festival, and the Taste of Coeur d'Alene is a food festival; the combined annual attendance is about 60,000 people.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Other notable events include Brewfest and the North Idaho State Fair.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene has become a destination for golf enthusiasts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is home to five golf courses and there are another eight more within 20 miles (32 km).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene Resort Golf Course features the world's only movable floating green.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] There is also the Circling Raven Golf Club at the Coeur d'Alene Casino resort, as well as several other private courses nearby, such the Tom Fazio-designed Gozzer Ranch.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene hosts some sporting events, and the event that receives the most attention is most likely the Ironman Coeur d'Alene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Ironman Triathlon alternates between full- and half-distance Ironman events on a rotating basis from year to year.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Other less intense and rigorous athletic events in town include the 15–108 mi (24–174 km) Coeur d'Fondo bike race and the Coeur d'Alene Crossing, a 2.4-mile (3.9 km) swimming challenge in which participants attempt to cross the lake.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene marathon is held annually at the end of May on the North Idaho Centennial Trail.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In amateur baseball, Coeur d'Alene fields a team in the American Legion Baseball league, the CDA Lumbermen.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In high school team sports, there is an annual rivalry game between the Coeur d'Alene High School Vikings and Lake City High School Timberwolves called the "Fight for the Fish".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The schools are the only two public high schools in the city and both compete in Idaho's Inland Empire League.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The community operates on a mayor–council government, where the mayor and the six councilors are each elected to four-year terms and the mayor leads the city council meetings on the first and third Tuesday of each month at Coeur d'Alene City Hall.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city is also the county seat of Kootenai County, Idaho.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] At the state level, The City of Coeur d'Alene is within Idaho Legislative District 2 and Idaho Legislative District 4 for the Idaho House of Representatives and Idaho Senate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] At the federal level, north Idaho is within Idaho's 1st congressional district and represented by Russ Fulcher in the United States House of Representatives and the state of Idaho by Mike Crapo and James Risch in the United States Senate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene, like the state of Idaho as a whole, is known for its conservative politics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The city and Kootenai County vote reliably conservative, and races at the federal and state level are often noncompetitive; local county and city partisan races are sometimes even uncontested.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The changing demographics of the county and region have altered the political landscape of the community and can be viewed as part of a nationwide ideological polarization trend.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is among a small group of cities in the United States that has elected a socialist mayor; they elected John T.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Wood, a Socialist Party of America member, to office in 1911 on a campaign platform of clean water, better health and sanitation standards, and anti-corruption.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The Coeur d'Alene School District serves around 11,000 students in 18 schools, including two traditional high schools, an alternative high school, three middle schools, eleven elementary schools, and a dropout retrieval school.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The first high school in the city, Coeur d'Alene High School, had its first building to house the students completed in 1904 and a second public high school, Lake City High School, was opened in 1994.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] District students who qualify are also eligible for dual enrollment with North Idaho College and the University of Idaho.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The district also has magnet schools that focus on specific curricula, such as the Sorensen Magnet School of the Arts and Humanities and Ramsey Magnet School of Science elementary schools and the Fernan STEM Academy, offering a STEM focus.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The district is the sixth-largest in the state and second-largest employer in Kootenai County.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene also has a charter school, the Coeur d'Alene Charter Academy.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Private and parochial schools augment the public school system, such as the PK-8 grade Roman Catholic Holy Family Catholic School and the PK-8 grade Seventh-day Adventist Lake City Academy.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Private schools that offer a full high school curriculum include the Coeur du Christ Academy, the PK-12 grade Classical Christian Academy and the 1–12 grade North Idaho Christian School.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The two latter are both non-denominational ASCI-accredited Christian schools located in Hayden.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Postsecondary education is fulfilled by North Idaho College, a public community college founded in 1933 as the Coeur d'Alene Junior College in downtown Coeur d'Alene on the former site of Fort Sherman.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The college has an enrollment of over 5,000 students and has outreach branches in Kellogg, Sandpoint, and Bonners Ferry.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The University of Idaho has a Coeur d'Alene presence and has a research park in the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is part of the Spokane television and radio media market and receives broadcasts in the Pacific Time Zone.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Coeur d'Alene is the city of license for some television and radio stations in the broadcast area, such as Idaho Public Television station, KCDT.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] In print media, Coeur d'Alene is also covered by Spokane's major daily newspaper, *The Spokesman-Review*, but the city has its own daily newspaper, the *Coeur d'Alene Press*, which covers issues in North Idaho and has an estimated circulation of about 17,300.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The publication was founded in 1892 by Joseph T.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] Scott and printed its first issue on February 20 of that year.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p01] The newspaper is among the properties of the Hagadone Corporation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] City roads are oriented in the four cardinal directions, with roads going north–south being designated as "streets" and roads going east–west as "avenues".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The greater Coeur d'Alene area is almost entirely dependent upon private automobiles for transportation, the city has a Walk Score of 36, indicating most errands require a car.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Combined with the city's rapid growth since 1990, relative congestion now occurs on a significant portion of the area highways, notably U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] 95 between Northwest Blvd. north to Hayden.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Public transportation played a significant role in Coeur d'Alene's early growth as a tourist destination.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] When an interurban electric railroad line was completed in 1903 from Spokane to the city, Inland Northwest residents often flocked to Lake Coeur d'Alene to enjoy being on the lake and going on steamboat cruises and other activities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The interurban electric line would later become the Spokane and Inland Empire Railroad.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The steamboats on Lake Coeur d'Alene were not only used to transport goods such as ore and timber, but also people.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] More steamboats operated on Lake Coeur d'Alene than on any other lake west of the Great Lakes, and there were intense rivalries between the steamboat lines.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The electric railroad and steam navigation on Lake Coeur d'Alene lasted until the late 1930s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Free public bus service is available to riders, provided by Citylink.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Intercity bus service to the city is provided by Jefferson Lines.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene does not have a passenger railroad station.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The closest Amtrak stations are Spokane and Sandpoint, both of which are served by Amtrak's Empire Builder.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene Airport – Pappy Boyington Field serves as a general aviation airport in Hayden, north of the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Near the marina on Lake Coeur d'Alene is the Brooks Seaplane Base (S76), which is a city-owned, public-use seaplane base for general aviation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] It is used mostly for air taxi purposes to conduct tours of Lake Coeur d'Alene and Lake Pend Oreille.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The nearest airport with commercial passenger flights is Spokane International Airport.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The city of Coeur d'Alene provides billing services for municipal water, sewer and stormwater management, street lighting, garbage collection, and recycling; Kootenai Electric Cooperative provides power and Avista Utilities provides both power and natural gas services in the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The city draws its water supply from the Spokane Valley–Rathdrum Prairie Aquifer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Telecom services such as television, internet, and telephone service are provided by vendors including Frontier Communications, Spectrum, Time Warner, and TDS Telecom.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The Post Falls hydroelectric dam on the Spokane River was built in 1906 and has a generation capacity of 14.75 megawatts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Kootenai Health is the primary medical center serving the Coeur d'Alene and North Idaho communities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The 329-bed community hospital is a Level III trauma center and is the largest employer in Kootenai County.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene also has a Veterans Affairs Community Based Outpatient Clinic (CBOC), the North Idaho CBOC, which has the Mann-Grandstaff VA Medical Center in Spokane as a parent facility.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene also has a few urgent care clinics operated by regional healthcare providers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Library services for the city of Coeur d'Alene are provided by two public libraries, the Coeur d'Alene Public Library in downtown and the Lake City Public Library near Lake City High School.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The Community Library Network maintains seven libraries in the wider communities in Kootenai and Shoshone counties, including branches in Post Falls, Hayden, Rathdrum, Spirit Lake, Athol, and Harrison.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Public library services in the area trace their roots to the Coeur d'Alene Women's Club in October 1904 and its operations and funding responsibilities were taken over by the city in May 1909.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The Coeur d'Alene Police Department was established in 1887, shortly after Coeur d'Alene was incorporated as a town; one of the first official acts the Board of Trustees took was to appoint a Town Marshal.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The police department has 103 police officers as of September 2020.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] In addition to the officers on staff, the department has a program called Officers Without Legal Standing (OWLS), which consists of retired law enforcement officers of various backgrounds from California who render assistance and aid as unpaid volunteers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene and North Idaho have been favored retirement destinations for former California law enforcement for decades, the trend being reported on as early as 1986 by the *Los Angeles Times*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] By the end of the 1990s, the number of retired California police officers in North Idaho numbered over 500; former LAPD detective Mark Fuhrman is among its residents.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The natural environment is among the chief attractions in the Coeur d'Alene area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The biggest natural attractions and parks include Tubbs Hill, City Park and Beach, and McEuen Park, all near downtown.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Tubbs Hill is a 120-acre (49 ha) park that is bordered by downtown Coeur d'Alene and McEuen Park to the north and the by Lake Coeur d'Alene on the south, east, and west sides.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The park features a somewhat rugged 2.2-mile (3.5 km) interpretive trail that offers views of the lake and the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] People often cliff jump into the lake from outcroppings in the park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] McEuen Park, which reopened in 2014 after a remodel, is a 22.5-acre (9.1 ha) park just north of Tubbs Hill that has a large playground, children's climbing rock, splash pad, two tennis/pickleball courts, four basketball courts, and an off leash dog park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] It also features a large pavilion and grassy amphitheater with concessions and restrooms for hosting large events as well as a boat launch and mooring facilities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Other recreation facilities include the Kroc Center, located near Ramsey Park just north of the Village at Riverstone, a multi-use venue with pool facilities and a fitness and recreation center.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] The North Idaho Centennial Trail passes through the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/coeur-d-alene-idaho-p02] Coeur d'Alene has one sister city, which is the Canadian city of Cranbrook, British Columbia.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is named for Thomas Jefferson (1743–1826), the third President of the United States, 1801–1809, and earlier major author of the Declaration of Independence of the United States on July 4, 1776.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] He also served several diplomatic posts overseas in Europe and was the first U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Secretary of State (1790–1793) in the first President's Cabinet of George Washington, and subsequently the second Vice President (1797–1801) under second chief executive John Adams.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is located on the northern edge of the Ozark Plateau on the southern side of the Missouri River in a region known as Mid-Missouri, that is roughly mid-way between the state's two large urban areas of Kansas City to the west and St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Louis in the east (along the west bank of the Mississippi River).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] It is 29 miles (47 km) south of Columbia, Missouri, and sits at the western edge of the Missouri Rhineland, one of the major wine-producing regions of the Midwest.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The city is dominated by the monumental domed Missouri State Capitol, which rises from a bluff overlooking the nearby Missouri River to the north.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Lewis and Clark with their Corps of Discovery passed the bluff here on their historic expedition upriver in 1804, eventually journeying westward to the Pacific Northwest region and the Pacific Ocean, before Europeans or Americans established any settlement there.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Many of Jefferson City's primary employers are in service and manufacturing industries like Hitachi.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is also home to Lincoln University, a public historically black and federal land-grant university founded the year after the American Civil War in 1866, by the Union Army black veterans of the First Missouri Regiment of Colored Infantry & 62nd Regiment of U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Colored Troops with support from the Second Missouri Regiment of Colored Infantry / 65th Regiment of U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] In pre-Columbian times, this region was home of an ancient people known today as the Mound Builders, likely related to the Mississippian societies.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] They were subsequently replaced by Osage Native Americans.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] In the late 17th century, frontiersmen began to inhabit the area, including Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac, Louis Jolliet, Jacques Marquette, Robert de LaSalle, and Daniel Boone, with the latter having the greatest influence on the region.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Famed Western explorer and settler Daniel Boone's son, Daniel Morgan Boone (1769–1839), would later lay out and plat Jefferson City in the early 19th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] When the Missouri Territory was organized in 1812, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Louis was Missouri's seat of government for the territorial governor and territorial legislature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Charles would serve as the next capital town of the old Territory.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City was chosen as the new state capital in 1821, after Missouri was admitted to the Union as the 24th State.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Over the years, the city was most often referred to as "Jefferson City"; the common name eventually stuck.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] For years, this village was little more than a trading post located in the wilderness about midway between St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] In 1825, the settlement was formally incorporated, and a year later, the state legislature of the General Assembly of Missouri moved to Jefferson City, where they would continue to meet.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City was also chosen by the lawmakers as the site of a state prison.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] This prison, named the Missouri State Penitentiary, opened in 1836.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] This prison was the unfortunate home to multiple infamous Americans, including former heavyweight boxing champion Sonny Liston, Martin Luther King Jr. assassin James Earl Ray, and infamous 1930s bank robber Pretty Boy Floyd.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), Jefferson City was occupied by Union / Federal troops.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The elected state legislature of the General Assembly were driven from Jefferson City by Union Army General Nathaniel Lyon (1818–1861).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Some of the rebelling legislators later reconvened in nearby Neosho and passed an ordinance of secession from the Federal Union.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Missouri was claimed by both the southern Confederacy and the Federal Union of the remaining United States, as was neighboring border state of Kentucky to the east, also split by the impending conflict of civil war.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Missourians were strongly divided and many people in the state—especially in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Louis—supported the Union, while other areas of the state, such as Missouri's Little Dixie were strongly pro-Confederate, further west along the Missouri River between Jefferson City and Kansas City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] German immigrants created vineyards in small towns on either side of the Missouri River, especially on the north from the city east to Marthasville, located outside of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Known as the "Missouri Rhineland" for its vineyards and first established by German immigrants in the mid-1800s, this region has become part of Missouri's agricultural and tourist economy.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Approximately 15 minutes before midnight on May 22, 2019, a tornado emergency was issued for the Jefferson City area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Minutes later, a destructive EF3 tornado caused extensive damage on the southwest side of the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] At least 20 people were injured, but none were killed due to this tornado.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The tornado originally touched down west of Eldon before heading its way to Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 37.58 square miles (97.33 km2), of which 35.95 square miles (93.11 km2) is land and 1.63 square miles (4.22 km2) is water.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City has a humid continental climate (Köppen *Dfa*) with hot, rainy summers and cold winters.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The city borders on having a humid subtropical climate but falls just short due to January having a mean temperature of 30 °F (−1 °C) which is below the 32 °F (0 °C) isotherm.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Thunderstorms are common in both the spring and summer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Light snow is common during the winter, although about half of wintertime precipitation falls as rain.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] As of the 2020 census, Jefferson City had a population of 43,228 in 17,305 households and 9,327 families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] 20.1% of residents were under the age of 18 and 17.7% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] For every 100 females there were 107.0 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 107.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] 91.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 8.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Among households, 26.6% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Of all households, 39.2% were married-couple households, 20.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 33.8% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] About 37.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] There were 19,219 housing units, of which 10.0% were vacant.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.1% and the rental vacancy rate was 9.2%.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The 2016-2020 5-year American Community Survey estimates show that the median household income was $54,003 (with a margin of error of ± $2,176) and the median family income was $75,490 (± $7,940).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The median income for those above 16 years old was $32,642 (± $2,031).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Approximately, 8.8% of families and 11.9% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.8% of those under the age of 18 and 6.9% of those ages 65 or over.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] At the 2010 census, there were 43,079 people in 17,278 households, including 9,969 families, in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The population density was 1,198.3 inhabitants per square mile (462.7/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] There were 18,852 housing units at an average density of 524.4 units per square mile (202.5 units/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The racial makeup of the city was 78.0% White, 16.9% African American, 0.3% Native American, 1.8% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.8% from other races, and 2.2% from two or more races.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 2.6%.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Of the 17,278 households 28.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.6% were married couples living together, 12.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 42.3% were non-families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] 36.2% of households were one person and 11.5% were one person aged 65 or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The average household size was 2.21 and the average family size was 2.89.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The age distribution was 20.9% of residents under the age of 18, 10.3% between the ages of 18 and 24, 28.6% from 25 to 44, 26.8% from 45 to 64, and 13.4% 65 or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The gender makeup of the city was 51.2% male and 48.8% female.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] At the 2000 census, there were 39,636 people in 15,794 households, including 9,207 families, in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The population density was 1,454.4 inhabitants per square mile (561.5/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] There were 16,987 housing units at an average density of 623.3 units per square mile (240.7 units/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The racial makeup of the city was 81.5% White, 14.7% Black or African American, 0.4% Native American, 1.2% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.6% from other races, and 1.5% from two or more races.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] 1.6% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Of the 15,794 households 27.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 44.4% were married couples living together, 10.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 41.7% were non-families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] 36.1% of households were one person and 11.9% were one person aged 65 or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The average household size was 2.21 and the average family size was 2.90.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] For every 100 females, there were 105.3 males.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 106.6 males.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The median household income was $39,628 and the median family income was $52,627.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Males had a median income of $35,050 versus $25,521 for females.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The per capita income for the city was $21,268.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] About 7.3% of families and 11.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.1% of those under age 18 and 7.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City's economy is driven by its residents, citizens of surrounding communities, and tourists.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City's economy relies on government, health care, manufacturing, retail, education, and tourism.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] In 2016, Jefferson City's gross metropolitan product was $7.366 billion and Missouri's real total gross domestic product was $260.309 billion; therefore, Jefferson City's economy accounted for 2.829% of the state's total gross domestic product.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Central Bancompany, Hawthorn Bancshares, Capital Region Medical Center, and Arris Pizza all have their headquarters in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is also home to Central Dairy, whose products are shipped statewide.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Tourists are drawn to the Missouri State Capitol, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Peter Church (adjacent to the capitol), Missouri State Penitentiary, Missouri Governor's Mansion, and Missouri State Museum.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] News & World Report* in 2007 as a top educational institution for international students, also helps draw students and tourists from other states and countries.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The State Capitol is located in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] In addition, state agencies are headquartered in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The Missouri State Archives is located in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The Missouri Department of Corrections (MDOC) operates the Jefferson City Correctional Center (JCCC) and the Algoa Correctional Center (ACC) in Jefferson City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] JCCC replaced the Missouri State Penitentiary in September 2004, which until its closure was the oldest operating penal facility west of the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] It served as the State of Missouri's primary maximum security institution, and it housed male death row prisoners until April 1989, when they were moved to the Potosi Correctional Center.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The United States Postal Service operates several postal facilities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The Jefferson City Main Post Office building previously shared occupancy with the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] District Court from its dedication in November 1934 until September 2011, when it moved into the Christopher S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The 118,000-square-foot courthouse is named for the former Governor and United States Senator from Missouri.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The courthouse, which is occupied by the Central Division of the United States District Court for the Western District of Missouri and under the appellate jurisdiction of the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit, was designed to achieve the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Green Building Council's LEED Gold rating.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Sustainable design features include reducing water use by 44 percent, using 13 percent recycled content, and diverting 80 percent of construction waste materials from landfills.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The building is 36 percent more efficient than current energy standards.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City Public School District operates Jefferson City High School and Capital City High School, two middle schools, Thomas Jefferson Middle School, and Lewis and Clark Middle School, and eleven elementary schools.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] There are five private elementary schools and three private high schools, including Helias High School and Calvary Lutheran High School in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Lincoln University is a public historically black university with open enrollment and certificate, associate, bachelor, and graduate programs.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Columbia College, William Woods University, Metro Business College, and Merrell University have campuses in the city, with varying degree levels and options.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The University of Missouri, the state's flagship university, is 30 miles to the north in Columbia.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City has a public library, the Missouri River Regional Library.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The major daily English-language newspaper in the area is the *Jefferson City News Tribune*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Several monthly magazines cover Jefferson City and/or the surrounding areas: *Jefferson City Magazine*, *Her Magazine*, *Capital Lifestyles*, and *Professional Day*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City, along with Columbia, is part of the Mid-Missouri television market.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] KRCG, the region's CBS affiliate, and KFDR, a station owned by the Christian Television Network (CTN), are both licensed to the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Missouri Routes 179 and 94 also run through the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is one of the four state capitals that is not served by an Interstate highway.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The others are Dover, Delaware; Juneau, Alaska; and Pierre, South Dakota.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Interstate 70 passes by the city 30 miles (48 km) to the north in Columbia.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The city is served by Columbia Regional Airport and nearby Jefferson City Memorial Airport.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] JeffTran, the city operated public transit system, provides year-round bus service during traditional weekday business hours, but is currently considering the extension of service hours to include evenings and weekends.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] The Jefferson City station, located in the former Union Hotel at Jefferson Landing State Historic Site, is one of the *Missouri River Runner* train stops between Kansas City and St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] A Greyhound bus stop near the Eastland Drive Convenient Food Mart also provides intercity transit.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City Memorial Airport, which is located in the Jefferson City limits of Callaway County, Missouri, serves general aviation but has no scheduled commercial airline service.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is home to SSM Health St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Capital Region Medical Center, an affiliate of University of Missouri Health Care, is located in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Jefferson City is the sister city to the German city of Münchberg.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/jefferson-city-missouri] Around 200 years ago, settlers from Münchberg founded a neighborhood south of downtown Jefferson City, which is still known as "Old Munichburg".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The **Missouri Department of Conservation** (**MDC**) and the **Missouri Conservation Commission** were created by Article IV Sections 40-42 of the Missouri Constitution, which were adopted by the voters of the state in 1936 as Amendment 4 to the constitution.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The Commission is vested with control, management, restoration, conservation, and regulation of fish, forest, and wildlife resources of the state.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The Department of Conservation owns and oversees hatcheries, sanctuaries, refuges, and reservations, and enforces the state wildlife code.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The Commission consists of four individuals appointed by the Governor of Missouri to serve unpaid 6-year terms.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] No more than two of the individuals may be from the same political party.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] As of June 2024, the tenth and current director of the Department of Conservation is Jason Summers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The department publishes the *Missouri Conservationist*, a monthly periodical that is free to all residents of the state of Missouri.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The MDC administers hundreds of parcels of land in all counties of the state.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] Most areas are owned by the department, but some are leased to the department, and some areas are leased by the department to other entities for management.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The department only acquires land from willing sellers and compensates local taxing authorities for the loss of property taxes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/missouri-department-of-conservation] The department has divided the counties of the state into eight administrative regions for the purpose of managing these lands and providing conservation services to the citizens of the state.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had been occupied by Native American cultures for thousands of years before European settlement.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city was founded on February 14, 1764, by French fur traders Gilbert Antoine de St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Maxent, Pierre Laclède, and Auguste Chouteau.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] They named it for King Louis IX of France, and it quickly became the regional center of the French Illinois Country.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis as part of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis developed as a major port on the Mississippi River; from 1870 until the 1920 census, it was the fourth-largest city in the country.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis County in 1877, becoming an independent city and limiting its political boundaries.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1904, it hosted the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, also known as the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis World's Fair, and the Summer Olympics.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is designated as one of 173 global cities by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has a diverse economy with strengths in the service, manufacturing, trade, transportation, and aviation industries.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] It is home to fourteen *Fortune* 1000 companies, seven of which are also *Fortune* 500 companies.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Federal agencies headquartered in the city or with significant operations there include the Federal Reserve Bank of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Department of Agriculture, and the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city's attractions include the 630-foot (192 m) Gateway Arch, the Saint Louis Zoo, Forest Park, the City Museum, the Missouri Botanical Garden, the Saint Louis Science Center, and the Saint Louis Art Museum.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Major research universities in Greater St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis include Washington University in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, Saint Louis University, and the University of Missouri–St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Washington University Medical Center hosts an agglomeration of medical and pharmaceutical institutions, including Barnes-Jewish Hospital.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has four professional sports teams: the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Cardinals of Major League Baseball, the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Blues of the National Hockey League, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis City SC of Major League Soccer, and the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Battlehawks of the United Football League.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was a center of the Native American Mississippian culture, which built numerous temple and residential earthwork mounds on both sides of the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Their major regional center was at Cahokia Mounds, active from 900 to 1500.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Due to numerous major earthworks within St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis boundaries, the city was nicknamed "Mound City".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] These mounds were mostly demolished during the city's development.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Historic Native American tribes in the area encountered by early Europeans included the Siouan-speaking Osage people, whose territory extended west, and the Illiniwek.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was repatriated to the Osage Nation in 2025.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] European exploration of the area was first recorded in 1673, when French explorers Louis Jolliet and Jacques Marquette traveled through the Mississippi River valley.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Five years later, La Salle claimed the region for France as part of La Louisiane, also known as Louisiana.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The earliest European settlements in the Illinois Country (also known as Upper Louisiana) were built by the French during the 1690s and early 1700s at Cahokia, Kaskaskia, and Fort de Chartres.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Migrants from the French villages on the east side of the Mississippi River, such as Kaskaskia, also founded Ste.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1764, after France lost the Seven Years' War, Pierre Laclède and his stepson Auguste Chouteau founded what was to become the city of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] (French lands east of the Mississippi had been ceded to Great Britain and the lands west of the Mississippi to Spain; Catholic France and Spain were 18th-century allies.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis XV of France and Charles III of Spain were cousins, both from the House of Bourbon.) The French families built the city's economy on the fur trade with the Osage, and with more distant tribes along the Missouri River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Chouteau brothers gained a monopoly from Spain on the fur trade with Santa Fe.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] French colonists used African slaves as domestic servants and workers in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] During the negotiations for the 1763 Treaty of Paris, French negotiators agreed to transfer France's colonial territories west of the Mississippi and Missouri rivers to New Spain to compensate for Spanish territorial losses during the war.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] These areas remained under Spanish control until 1803, when they were transferred to the French First Republic.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] During the American Revolutionary War, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was unsuccessfully attacked by British-allied Native Americans in the 1780 Battle of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was preceded by a trading business between Gilbert Antoine de St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Maxent and Pierre Laclède (Liguest) in late 1763.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Maxent invested in a Mississippi River expedition led by Laclède, who searched for a location to base the company's fur trading operations.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Genevieve was already established as a trading center, he sought a place less prone to flooding.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] He found an elevated area overlooking the flood plain of the Mississippi River, not far south from its confluence with the Missouri and Illinois rivers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In addition to having an advantageous natural drainage system, there were nearby forested areas to supply timber and grasslands which could easily be converted for agricultural purposes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Laclède declared that this place "might become, hereafter, one of the finest cities in America".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] He dispatched his 14-year-old stepson, Auguste Chouteau, to the site, with the support of 30 settlers in February 1764.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Laclède arrived at the future town site two months later and produced a plan for St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis based on the New Orleans street plan.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The default block size was 240 by 300 feet, with just three long avenues running parallel to the west bank of the Mississippi.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] He established a public corridor of 300 feet fronting the river, but later this area was released for private development.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] For the city's first few years, it was not recognized by any governments.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Although the settlement was thought to be under the control of the Spanish government, no one asserted any authority over it, and thus St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] This vacuum led Laclède to assume civil control, and all problems were disposed in public settings, such as communal meetings.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In addition, Laclède granted new settlers lots in town and the surrounding countryside.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In hindsight, many of these original settlers thought of these first few years as "the golden age of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1763, the Native Americans in the region around St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis began expressing dissatisfaction with the victorious British, objecting to their refusal to continue to the French tradition of supplying gifts to Natives.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Odawa chieftain Pontiac began forming a pan-tribal alliance to counter British control over the region but received little support from the indigenous residents of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] By 1765, the city began receiving visits from representatives of the British, French, and Spanish governments.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was transferred to the French First Republic in 1800 (although all of the colonial lands continued to be administered by Spanish officials), then sold by the French to the U.S. in 1803 as part of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis became the capital of, and gateway to, the new territory.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Shortly after the official transfer of authority was made, the Lewis and Clark Expedition was commissioned by President Thomas Jefferson.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis in May 1804 along the Missouri River to explore the vast territory.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] There were hopes of finding a water route to the Pacific Ocean, but the party had to go overland in the Upper West.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] They reached the Pacific Ocean via the Columbia River in summer 1805.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Many other explorers, settlers, and trappers (such as Ashley's Hundred) would later take a similar route to the West.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city elected its first municipal legislators (called trustees) in 1808.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis in 1817, improving connections with New Orleans and eastern markets.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Missouri was admitted as a state in 1821.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was incorporated as a city in 1822, and continued to develop largely due to its busy port and trade connections.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Immigrants from Ireland and Germany arrived in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis in significant numbers starting in the 1840s, and the population of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had a greater population than New Orleans.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Settled by many Southerners in a slave state, the city was split in political sympathies and became polarized during the American Civil War.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In the decades preceding the war, tensions ran high between abolitionists and pro-slavery residents, exemplified by the repeated destruction of abolitionist Elijah Parish Lovejoy's printing press and his eventual murder by a mob in nearby Alton, Illinois in 1837.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1861, 28 civilians were killed in a clash with Union troops.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis economically, due to the Union blockade of river traffic to the south on the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Arsenal constructed ironclads for the Union Navy.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Slaves worked in many jobs on the waterfront and on the riverboats.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Given the city's location close to the free state of Illinois and others, some slaves escaped to freedom.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Others, especially women with children, sued in court in freedom suits, and several prominent local attorneys aided slaves in these suits.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] About half the slaves achieved freedom in hundreds of suits before the American Civil War began in 1861.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis profited via trade with the West, aided by the 1874 completion of the Eads Bridge, named for its design engineer.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Industrial developments on both banks of the river were linked by the bridge, the second in the Midwest over the Mississippi River after the Hennepin Avenue Bridge in Minneapolis.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Eads Bridge became a symbolic image of the city of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, from the time of its erection until 1965 when the Gateway Arch Bridge was constructed.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis riverfront between Laclede's Landing, to the north, and the grounds of the Gateway Arch, to the south.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Today the road deck has been restored, allowing vehicular and pedestrian traffic to cross the river.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis MetroLink light rail system has used the rail deck since 1993.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] An estimated 8,500 vehicles pass through it daily.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis County and become an independent city, and, following a recount of the votes in November, officially did so in March 1877.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis general strike caused significant upheaval, in a fight for the eight-hour day and the banning of child labor.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Industrial production continued to increase during the late 19th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Major corporations such as the Anheuser-Busch brewery, Ralston Purina company and Desloge Consolidated Lead Company were established at St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis which was also home to several brass era automobile companies, including the Success Automobile Manufacturing Company; St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is the site of the Wainwright Building, a skyscraper designed in 1892 by architect Louis Sullivan.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1900, the entire streetcar system was shut down by a several months-long strike, with significant unrest occurring in the city & violence against the striking workers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1904, the city hosted the World's Fair and the Olympics, becoming the first non-European city to host the games.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The formal name for the 1904 World's Fair was the Louisiana Purchase Exposition.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Permanent facilities and structures remaining from the fair are located in Forest Park, and other notable structures within the park's boundaries include the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Zoo and the Missouri History Museum, and Tower Grove Park and the Botanical Gardens.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] After the Civil War, social and racial discrimination in housing and employment were common in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis passed a residential segregation ordinance saying that if 75% of the residents of a neighborhood were of a certain race, no one from a different race was allowed to move in.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] That ordinance was struck down in a court challenge, by the NAACP, after which racial covenants were used to prevent the sale of houses in certain neighborhoods to "persons not of Caucasian race".
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louisans offered a lawsuit in challenge, and such covenants were ruled unconstitutional by the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1926, Douglass University, a historically black university was founded by B.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, and at the time no other college in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In the first half of the 20th century, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was a destination in the Great Migration of African Americans from the rural South seeking better opportunities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] During World War II, the NAACP campaigned to integrate war factories.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1964, civil rights activists protested at the construction of the Gateway Arch to publicize their effort to gain entry for African Americans into the skilled trade unions, where they were underrepresented.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Department of Justice filed the first suit against the unions under the Civil Rights Act of 1964.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, had about 220 automakers, close to 10 percent of all American carmakers, about half of which built cars exclusively in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Notable names include Dorris, Gardner and Moon.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had some of the worst air pollution in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In April 1940, the city banned the use of soft coal mined in nearby states.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city hired inspectors to ensure that only anthracite was burned.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] By 1946, the city had reduced air pollution by about 75%.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, like many Midwestern cities, expanded in the early 20th century due to industrialization, which provided jobs to new generations of immigrants and migrants from the South.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] It reached its peak population of 856,796 at the 1950 census.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Suburbanization from the 1950s through the 1990s dramatically reduced the city's population, as did restructuring of industry and loss of jobs.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The effects of suburbanization were exacerbated by the small geographical size of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis due to its earlier decision to become an independent city, and it lost much of its tax base.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] During the 19th and 20th century, most major cities aggressively annexed surrounding areas as residential development occurred away from the central city; however, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Several urban renewal projects were built in the 1950s, as the city worked to replace old and substandard housing.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Some of these were poorly designed and resulted in problems.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] One prominent example, Pruitt–Igoe, became a symbol of failure in public housing, and was torn down less than two decades after it was built.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The degradation and razing of Mill Creek Valley in this time was featured as an example of disenfranchisement in the 2024 Reparations Commission Report.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Since the 1980s, several revitalization efforts have focused on Downtown St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The urban revitalization projects that started in the 1980s continued into the new century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city's old garment district, centered on Washington Avenue in the Downtown and Downtown West neighborhoods, experienced major development starting in the late 1990s as many of the old factory and warehouse buildings were converted into lofts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The American Planning Association designated Washington Avenue as one of 10 Great Streets for 2011.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Cortex Innovation Community, located within the city's Central West End neighborhood, was founded in 2002 and has become a multi-billion dollar economic engine for the region, with companies such as Microsoft and Boeing currently leasing office space.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Forest Park Southeast neighborhood in the central corridor has seen major investment starting in the early 2010s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Between 2013 and 2018, over $50 million worth of residential construction has been built in the neighborhood.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The population of the neighborhood has increased by 19% from the 2010 to 2020 Census.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Rams of the National Football League controversially returned to Los Angeles in 2016.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis sued the NFL in 2017, alleging the league breached its relocation guidelines to profit at the expense of the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 2021, the NFL and Rams owner Stan Kroenke agreed to settle out of court with the city for $790 million.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] On May 16, 2025, a 1.8 mile wide EF3 tornado struck northern parts of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] According to mayor Cara Spencer, the tornado produced up to $1.6 billion in damage, and governor Mike Kehoe stated on behalf of FEMA that the scope of residential damage was the worst since the Joplin tornado over a decade prior.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has a total area of 66 square miles (170 km2), of which 62 square miles (160 km2) is land and 4.1 square miles (11 km2) (6.2%) is water.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city is built on bluffs and terraces that rise 100–200 feet above the western banks of the Mississippi River, just south its confluence with the Missouri River and directly across from Illinois.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The eastern city limits follow the Mississippi River as the state border.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Much of the area is a fertile and gently rolling prairie that features low hills and broad, shallow valleys.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Both the Mississippi River and the Missouri River have cut large valleys with wide flood plains.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Near the southern boundary of the city of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis County) is the River des Peres, practically the only river or stream within the city limits that is not entirely underground.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most of River des Peres was confined to a channel or put underground in the 1920s and early 1930s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The lower section of the river was the site of some of the worst flooding of the Great Flood of 1993.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis area experienced a significant flood in 1973, primarily caused by the Mississippi River reaching its highest level in over 150 years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] While heavy rainfall and snowmelt contributed, the flood was exacerbated by a saturated drainage basin and high water levels in the Missouri River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The flooding led to levee failures, inundation of homes, businesses, and parkland, and prompted evacuations and sandbagging efforts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Limestone and dolomite of the Mississippian epoch underlie the area, and parts of the city are karst in nature.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] This is particularly true of the area south of downtown, which has numerous sinkholes and caves.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most of the caves in the city have been sealed, but many springs are visible along the riverfront.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Coal, brick clay, and millerite ore were once mined in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The predominant surface rock, known as *St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis limestone*, is used as dimension stone and rubble for construction.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] are built with a blending of Greek Revival, Federal and Italianate styles.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis exhibits a variety of commercial, residential, and monumental architecture.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is known for the Gateway Arch, the tallest monument constructed in the United States at 630 feet (190 m).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Arch pays homage to Thomas Jefferson and St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis's position as the gateway to the West.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Architectural influences reflected in the area include French Colonial, German, early American, and modern architectural styles.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Several examples of religious structures are extant from the pre-Civil War period, and most reflect the common residential styles of the time.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Among the earliest is the Basilica of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, King of France (referred to as the *Old Cathedral*).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Basilica was built between 1831 and 1834 in the Federal style.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Other religious buildings from the period include SS.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Cyril and Methodius Church (1857) in the Romanesque Revival style and Christ Church Cathedral (completed in 1867, designed in 1859) in the Gothic Revival style.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] A few civic buildings were constructed during the early 19th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis courthouse was built in 1826 and featured a Federal style stone facade with a rounded portico.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] However, this courthouse was replaced during renovation and expansion of the building in the 1850s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis County Courthouse (known as the *Old Courthouse*) was completed in 1864 and was notable for having a cast iron dome and for being the tallest structure in Missouri until 1894.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Finally, a customs house was constructed in the Greek Revival style in 1852, but was demolished and replaced in 1873 by the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Because much of the city's commercial and industrial development was centered along the riverfront, many pre-Civil War buildings were demolished during construction of the Gateway Arch.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city's remaining architectural heritage of the era includes a multi-block district of cobblestone streets and brick and cast-iron warehouses called Laclede's Landing.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Now popular for its restaurants and nightclubs, the district is located north of Gateway Arch along the riverfront.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Other industrial buildings from the era include some portions of the Anheuser-Busch Brewery, which date to the 1860s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis saw a vast expansion in variety and number of religious buildings during the late 19th century and early 20th century.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The largest and most ornate of these is the Cathedral Basilica of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Barnett and constructed between 1907 and 1914 in the Neo-Byzantine style.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Cathedral, as it is known, has one of the largest mosaic collections in the world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Another landmark in religious architecture of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Stanislaus Kostka, which is an example of the Polish Cathedral style.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Among the other major designs of the period were St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Alphonsus Liguori (known as *The Rock Church*) (1867) in the Gothic Revival and Second Presbyterian Church of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis (1900) in Richardsonian Romanesque.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was the fourth largest city in the country.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 1904, the city hosted a world's fair at Forest Park called the Louisiana Purchase Exposition.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Its architectural legacy is somewhat scattered.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Among the fair-related cultural institutions in the park are the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Art Museum designed by Cass Gilbert, part of the remaining lagoon at the foot of Art Hill, and the Flight Cage at the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Missouri History Museum was built afterward, with the profit from the fair.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] But 1904 left other assets to the city, like Theodore Link's 1894 St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Union Station, and an improved Forest Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] One US Bank Plaza, the local headquarters for US Bancorp, was constructed in 1976 in the structural expressionist style.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Several notable postmodern commercial skyscrapers were built downtown in the 1970s and 1980s, including the former AT&T building at 909 Chestnut Street (1986), and One Metropolitan Square (1989), which is the tallest building in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis saw the construction of the largest United States courthouse by area, the Thomas F.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Eagleton United States Courthouse (2000).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Eagleton Courthouse is home to the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Missouri and the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The most recent high-rise buildings in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis include two residential towers: One Hundred in the Central West End neighborhood and One Cardinal Way in the Downtown neighborhood.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city is divided into 79 officially-recognized neighborhoods.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen: *Cfa*); however, its metropolitan region even to the south may present a hot-summer humid continental climate (*Dfa*), which shows the effect of the urban heat island in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city experiences hot, humid summers and chilly to cold winters.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] It is subject to both cold Arctic air and hot, humid tropical air from the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The average annual temperature recorded at nearby Lambert–St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis International Airport, is 57.4 °F (14.1 °C).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] 100 and 0 °F (38 and −18 °C) temperatures can be seen on an average 3 and 1 days per year, respectively.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis experiences thunderstorms 48 days a year on average.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Especially in the spring, these storms can often be severe, with high winds, large hail and tornadoes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Lying within the hotbed of Tornado Alley, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is one of the most frequently tornado-struck metropolitan areas in the U.S. and has an extensive history of damaging tornadoes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Severe flooding, such as the Great Flood of 1993, may occur in spring and summer; the (often rapid) melting of thick snow cover upstream on the Missouri or Mississippi Rivers can contribute to springtime flooding.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Before the founding of the city, the area was mostly prairie and open forest.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Native Americans maintained this environment, good for hunting, by burning underbrush.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Trees are mainly oak, maple, and hickory, similar to the forests of the nearby Ozarks; common understory trees include eastern redbud, serviceberry, and flowering dogwood.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Riparian areas are forested with mainly American sycamore.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most of the residential areas of the city are planted with large native shade trees.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The largest native forest area is found in Forest Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In autumn, the changing color of the trees is notable.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most species here are typical of the eastern woodland, although numerous decorative non-native species are found.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The most notable invasive species is Japanese honeysuckle, which officials are trying to manage because of its damage to native trees.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Wildlife includes urbanized coyotes, white-tailed deer, eastern gray squirrel, cottontail rabbit, and the nocturnal Virginia opossum.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Large bird species are abundant in parks and include Canada goose, mallard duck, and shorebirds, including the great egret and great blue heron.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Gulls are common along the Mississippi River; these species follow barge traffic.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Winter populations of bald eagles are along the Mississippi River around the Chain of Rocks Bridge.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city is on the Mississippi Flyway, used by migrating birds, and has a large variety of small bird species, common to the eastern U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Eurasian tree sparrow, an introduced species, is limited in North America to the counties surrounding St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The city has special sites for birdwatching of migratory species, including Tower Grove Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Common frog species include the American toad and species of chorus frogs called spring peepers, which are found in nearly every pond.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Some years have outbreaks of cicadas or ladybugs.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Mosquitoes, no-see-ums, and houseflies are common insect nuisances, especially in July and August; because of this, windows are almost always fitted with screens.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Invasive populations of honeybees have declined in recent years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Numerous native species of pollinator insects have recovered to fill their ecological niche, and armadillos are throughout the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis grew slowly until the American Civil War, when industrialization and immigration sparked a boom.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Mid-19th century immigrants included many Irish and Germans; later there were immigrants from southern and eastern Europe.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In the early 20th century, African American and white migrants came from the South; the former as part of the Great Migration out of rural areas of the Deep South.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Many came from Mississippi and Arkansas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Italians, Serbians, Lebanese, Syrians, and Greeks settled in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] After years of immigration, migration, and expansion, the city reached its peak population in 1950.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] That year, the Census Bureau reported St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis's population as 82% White and 17.9% African American.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis began losing population to the suburbs, first because of increased demand for new housing, unhappiness with city services, ease of commuting by highways, and later, white flight.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis's population decline has resulted in a significant increase of abandoned residential housing units and vacant lots throughout the city proper; this blight has attracted much wildlife (such as deer and coyotes) to the many abandoned overgrown lots.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has lost 64.8% of its population since the 1950 United States census.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] During this period, the population of Greater St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, which includes more than one county, has grown every year and continues to do so.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] According to the 2010 United States census, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had 319,294 people living in 142,057 households, of which 67,488 households were families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The population density was 5,158.2 people per square mile (1,991.6 people/km2).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] About 24% of the population was 19 or younger, 9% were 20 to 24, 31% were 25 to 44, 25% were 45 to 64, and 11% were 65 or older.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The African-American population is concentrated in the north side of the city (the area north of Delmar Boulevard is 94.0% black, compared with 35.0% in the central corridor and 26.0% in the south side of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Among the Asian-American population in the city, the largest ethnic group is Vietnamese (0.9%), followed by Chinese (0.6%) and Indians (0.5%).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Vietnamese community has concentrated in the Dutchtown neighborhood of south St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis; Chinese are concentrated in the Central West End.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] People of Mexican descent are the largest Latino group, and make up 2.2% of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] They have the highest concentration in the Dutchtown, Benton Park West (Cherokee Street), and Gravois Park neighborhoods.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] People of Italian descent are concentrated in The Hill.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis's per-capita rates of online charitable donations and volunteerism were among the highest among major U.S. cities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis's population age 5 and older spoke a mother language other than English.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] About fifteen families from Bosnia settled in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] After the Bosnian War started in 1992, more Bosnian refugees began arriving and by 2000, tens of thousands of Bosnian refugees settled in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis with the help of Catholic aid societies.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Many of them were professionals and skilled workers who had to take any job opportunity to be able to support their families.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most Bosnian refugees are Muslim, ethnically Bosniaks (87%); they have settled primarily in south St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Bosnian-Americans are well integrated into the city, developing many businesses and ethnic/cultural organizations.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] An estimated 70,000 Bosnians live in the metro area, which is tied with Chicago for largest population of Bosnians in the United States and the largest Bosnian population outside their homeland.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The highest concentration of Bosnians is in the neighborhood of Bevo Mill and in Affton, Mehlville, and Oakville of south St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Bosnian Muslim Romani people have also settled in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has had, as of April 2017, one of the highest murder rates, per capita, in the United States, with 188 homicides in 2015 (59.3 homicides per 100,000) and ranks No.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] 13 of the most dangerous cities in the world by homicide rate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Detroit, Flint, Memphis, Birmingham, and Baltimore have higher overall violent crime rates than St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, when comparing other crimes such as rape, robbery, and aggravated assault.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] These crime rates are high relative to other American cities, but St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis index crime rates have declined almost every year since the peak in 1993 (16,648), to the 2014 level of 7,931 (which is the sum of violent crimes and property crimes) per 100,000.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] In 2015, the index crime rate reversed the 2005–2014 decline to a level of 8,204.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Between 2005 and 2014, violent crime has declined by 20%, although rates of violent crime remains 6 times higher than the United States national average and property crime in the city remains 2 1⁄2 times the national average.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has a higher homicide rate than the rest of the U.S. for both whites and blacks and a higher proportion committed by males.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] As of October 2016, 7 of the homicide suspects were white, 95 black, 0 Hispanic, 0 Asian and 1 female out of the 102 suspects.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was the most dangerous city in the United States with populations of 100,000 or more, ranking 1st in violent crime and 2nd in property crime.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] It was also ranked 6th of the most dangerous of all establishments in the United States, and East St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis, a suburb of the city itself, was ranked 1st.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Police Department at the end of 2016 reported a total of 188 murders for the year, the same number of homicides that had occurred in the city in 2015.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] According to the STLP At the end of 2017, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had 205 murders but the city recorded only 159 inside St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The new Chief of Police, John Hayden said two-thirds (67%) of all the murders and one-half of all the assaults are concentrated in a triangular area in the North part of the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Yet another factor when comparing the murder rates of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis and other cities is the manner of drawing municipal boundaries.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] While many other municipalities have annexed many suburbs, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis has not annexed as much suburban area as most American cities.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis metro area included about 3 million residents and the city included about 300,000 residents.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Therefore, the city contains about ten percent of the metro population, a low ratio indicating that the municipal boundaries include only a small part of the metro population.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The gross domestic product of Greater St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis was $226.5 billion in 2023, up from $211.5 billion the previous year.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis had a GDP per capita of $68,574 in 2021, up 10% from the previous year.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] As of November, 2024, the education and health services industries employed the greatest number of people in the region, followed by the trade, transportation, and utilities industries and professional and business services.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is home to seven *Fortune* 500 companies: Centene Corporation, Reinsurance Group of America, Emerson Electric, Edward Jones, Graybar Electric, Post Holdings, and Core & Main.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] An additional seven other area companies are listed on the *Fortune* 1000: Ameren Corporation, Olin Corporation, Stifel Financial, Peabody Energy, Advantage Solutions, Energizer Holdings, and Caleres.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Other major corporations headquartered in the region include Anheuser-Busch, Bunge Global, Wells Fargo Advisors, Enterprise Holdings, World Wide Technology, Arco Construction, McCarthy Holdings, Clayco Construction, Apex Oil, Alberici, and Schnuck Markets.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Several once-independent pillars of the local economy have been purchased by other corporations.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The May Department Stores Company was purchased by Federated Department Stores, now Macy's, although it still has its regional headquarters in the area.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Most of the assets of Furniture Brands International were sold to Heritage Home Group in 2013, which moved to North Carolina.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] German-based Bayer acquired Monsanto in 2018.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is one of two federal reserve banks in Missouri.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis is a center of medicine and biotechnology.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The Washington University School of Medicine is affiliated with Barnes-Jewish Hospital, the fifth largest hospital in the world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The School of Medicine also is affiliated with St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Children's Hospital, one of the country's top pediatric hospitals.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Both hospitals are owned by BJC HealthCare.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The McDonnell Genome Institute at Washington University played a major role in the Human Genome Project.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Saint Louis University Medical School is affiliated with SSM Health's Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital and Saint Louis University Hospital.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] It also has a cancer center, vaccine research center, geriatric center, and a bioethics institute.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Several different organizations operate hospitals in the area, including BJC HealthCare, Mercy, SSM Health Care, and Tenet.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Other health care and biotechnology institutions with operations in the region include Pfizer, the Donald Danforth Plant Science Center, Bayer, Sigma-Aldrich, Mallinckrodt, and Multidata Systems International.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Cortex Innovation Community in Midtown is the region's largest innovation hub.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Cortex is home to offices of Square, Microsoft, Aon, Boeing, and Centene.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Cortex has generated 3,800 tech jobs in 14 years, and once built out, is projected to generate $2 billion in development and create 13,000 jobs for the region.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] The nonprofit Arch Grants is attracting new startups to the region, while the nonprofit LaunchCode trains future tech workers.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p01] Louis Business Journal*, the top employers in Greater St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The same year as the 1904 World's Fair, the Strassberger Music Conservatory Building was constructed at 2300 Grand.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In 1911, the conservatory had over 1,100 students.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The building is presently in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] A well known graduate was Alfonso D'Artega.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] With its French past and waves of Catholic immigrants in the 19th and 20th centuries, from Ireland, Germany and Italy, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is a major center of Roman Catholicism in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis also boasts the largest Ethical Culture Society in the United States and is one of the most generous cities in the United States, ranking ninth in 2013.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Several places of worship in the city are noteworthy, such as the Cathedral Basilica of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, home of the world's largest mosaic installation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Other churches include the Basilica of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, King of France, the oldest Roman Catholic cathedral west of the Mississippi River and the oldest church in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Abbey, whose distinctive architectural style garnered multiple awards at the time of its completion in 1962; and St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Francis de Sales Oratory, a neo-Gothic church completed in 1908 in South St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis and the second largest church in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city is identified with music and the performing arts, especially blues, jazz, and ragtime.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Symphony is the second oldest symphony orchestra in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Until 2010, it was also home to KFUO-FM, one of the oldest classical music FM radio stations west of the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis has been called "one of America's best summer festivals" by the *Washington Post*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Former general director Timothy O'Leary was known for drawing the community into discussions of challenging operas.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] John Adams's "The Death of Klinghoffer", which touched off protests and controversy when performed by the Metropolitan Opera in 2014, had no such problems in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis three years before, because the company fostered a citywide discussion, with interfaith dialogues addressing the tough issues of terrorism, religion and the nature of evil that the opera brings up.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis's Jewish Community Relations Council gave O'Leary an award.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Under O'Leary, the company—always known for innovative work—gave second chances to other major American operas, such as John Corigliano's "The Ghosts of Versailles", presented in 2009 in a smaller-scale version.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis and a historic center that includes: the Federal courthouse where the Dred Scott case was first argued, an expanded public library, major churches and businesses, and retail.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] An increasing downtown residential population has taken to adapted office buildings and other historic structures.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In nearby University City is the Delmar Loop, ranked by the American Planning Association as a "great American street" for its variety of shops and restaurants, and the Tivoli Theater, all within walking distance.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Unique city and regional cuisine reflecting various immigrant groups include toasted ravioli, gooey butter cake, provel cheese, the slinger, the Gerber sandwich, and the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis chefs have begun emphasizing use of local produce, meats and fish, and neighborhood farmers' markets have become more popular.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Artisan bakeries, salumeria, and chocolatiers also operate in the city.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis-style pizza has thin crust, provel cheese, and is cut in small squares.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Frozen-custard purveyor Ted Drewes offers its "Concrete": frozen custard blended with any combination of dozens of ingredients into a mixture so thick that a spoon inserted into the custard does not fall if the cup is inverted.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Cardinals of Major League Baseball and the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Blues of the National Hockey League.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In 2019, it became the eighth North American city to have won titles in all four major leagues (MLB, NBA, NFL, and NHL) when the Blues won the Stanley Cup championship.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] It has collegiate-level soccer teams and is one of three American cities to have hosted the Summer Olympic Games.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis City SC of Major League Soccer, began play in 2023.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Cardinals are one of the most successful franchises in Major League Baseball.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Cardinals have won 19 National League (NL) titles (the most pennants for the league franchise in one city) and 11 World Series titles (second to the New York Yankees and the most by any NL franchise), recently in 2011.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Browns played in the American League (AL) from 1902 to 1953, before moving to Baltimore, Maryland to become the current incarnation of the Orioles.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Browns at Sportsman's Park, won by the Cardinals in six games.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] It was the third and final time that the teams shared a home field.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Giants from 1906 to 1921, who played in Negro league baseball from 1920 to 1931 and won championships in 1928, 1930, and 1931, and the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Maroons who played in the Union Association in 1884 and in the National League from 1885 to 1889.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Maroons won the Union Association pennant and started the season with 20 straight wins, a feat that was not surpassed by any major professional sports team in the United States until the 2015–16 Golden State Warriors season when they started their NBA season with 24 straight wins.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Blues of the National Hockey League (NHL) play at the Enterprise Center.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] They were one of the six teams added to the NHL in the 1967 expansion.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Blues went to the Stanley Cup finals in their first three years, but got swept every time.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Although they were the first 1967 expansion team to make the Stanley Cup Finals, they were also the last of the 1967 expansion teams to win the Stanley Cup.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] They finally won their first Stanley Cup in 2019 after beating the Boston Bruins in the final.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis the eighth city to win a championship in each of the four major U.S. sports.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Prior to the Blues, the city was home to the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis has been home to four National Football League (NFL) teams.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis All-Stars played in the city in 1923, the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Cardinals from 1960 to 1987, and the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The football Cardinals advanced to the NFL playoffs four times (1964, 1974, 1975 and 1982), never hosting in any appearance.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] They did, however, win the 1964 Playoff Bowl for third place against the Green Bay Packers by a score of 24–17.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Cardinals moved to Phoenix, Arizona, in 1988.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Rams played at the Edward Jones Dome from 1995 to 2015 and won Super Bowl XXXIV in 2000.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] They also went to Super Bowl XXXVI but lost to the New England Patriots.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Rams then returned to Los Angeles in 2016.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Hawks of the National Basketball Association (NBA) played at Kiel Auditorium from 1955 to 1968.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] They won the NBA championship in 1958 and played in three other NBA Finals: 1957, 1960, and 1961.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Bombers of the Basketball Association of America from 1946 to 1949 and the National Basketball Association from 1949 to 1950 and the Spirits of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis of the American Basketball Association from 1974 to 1976 when the ABA and NBA merged.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis City SC began play in 2023 at Energizer Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis City 2, which began play in 2022 and also plays at Energizer Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Formerly, USL Championship's Saint Louis FC played in the area from 2015 to 2020 at World Wide Technology Soccer Park.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis BattleHawks of the XFL began play in 2020, using The Dome at America's Center as their home field.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] After a two-year hiatus of the league, the Battlehawks returned in 2023, when the XFL resumed play.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis hosts several minor league sports teams.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Gateway Grizzlies of the independent Frontier League play in the area in Sauget, IL.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Trotters of the Independent Basketball Association play at Matthews-Dickey Boys and Girls Club.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Ambush indoor soccer team plays in nearby St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Charles at the Family Arena as a part of the Major Arena Soccer League.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Slam play in the Women's Football Alliance at Harlen C.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The region hosts INDYCAR, NHRA drag racing, and NASCAR events at World Wide Technology Raceway at Gateway in Madison, Illinois.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Thoroughbred flat racing events are hosted at Fairmount Park Racetrack near Collinsville, Illinois.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is home to the Saint Louis Chess Club where the U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louisan Rex Sinquefield founded the Chess Club and Scholastic Center of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Chess Club later) and moved the World Chess Hall of Fame to St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Sinquefield Cup Tournament started at St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In 2014 the Sinquefield Cup was the highest-rated chess tournament of all time.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Chess Champions Fabiano Caruana and Hikaru Nakamura have lived in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Former women's chess champion Susan Polgar also resides in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis has hosted the Final Four of both the women's and men's college basketball NCAA Division I championship tournaments, and the men's Frozen Four collegiate ice hockey tournament.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Saint Louis University has won 10 NCAA men's soccer championships, and the city has hosted the College Cup several times.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In addition to collegiate soccer, many St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louisans have played for the United States men's national soccer team, and 20 St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louisans have been elected into the National Soccer Hall of Fame.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis also is the origin of the sport of corkball, a type of baseball in which there is no base running.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Although the area does not have a National Basketball Association team, it hosts the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Phoenix, an American Basketball Association team.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Club Atletico Saint Louis, a semi-professional soccer team, competes within the National Premier Soccer League and plays out of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis University High School Soccer Stadium.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city operates more than 100 parks, with amenities that include sports facilities, playgrounds, concert areas, picnic areas, and lakes.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Forest Park, located on the western edge of city, is the largest, occupying 1,400 acres of land, making it almost twice as large as Central Park in New York City.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The park is home to five major institutions, including the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Science Center, the Missouri History Museum, and the Muny amphitheatre.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Another significant park in the city is Gateway Arch National Park, which was known as Jefferson National Expansion Memorial until 2018 and is located on the riverfront in downtown St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The centerpiece of the park is the 630-foot (192 m) tall Gateway Arch, a National Memorial designed by noted architect Eero Saarinen and completed on October 28, 1965.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Also part of the historic park is the Old Courthouse, where the first two trials of *Dred Scott v.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Other parks include the Missouri Botanical Garden, Tower Grove Park, Carondelet Park, and Citygarden.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Missouri Botanical Garden, a private garden and botanical research facility, is a National Historic Landmark and one of the oldest botanical gardens in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Garden features 79 acres of horticultural displays from around the world.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] This includes a Japanese strolling garden, Henry Shaw's original 1850 estate home and a geodesic dome called the Climatron.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Immediately south of the Missouri Botanical Garden is Tower Grove Park, a gift to the city by Henry Shaw.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Citygarden is an urban sculpture park located in downtown St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, with art from Fernand Léger, Aristide Maillol, Julian Opie, Tom Otterness, Niki de Saint Phalle, and Mark di Suvero.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The park is divided into three sections, each of which represent a different theme: river bluffs; flood plains; and urban gardens.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Another downtown sculpture park is the Serra Sculpture Park, with the 1982 Richard Serra sculpture *Twain*.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is one of the 41 independent cities in the U.S. that does not legally belong to any county.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis has a strong mayor–council government with legislative authority and oversight vested in the Board of Aldermen and with executive authority in the mayor and six other elected officials.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The mayor is the chief executive officer of the city and is responsible for appointing city department heads.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Board of Aldermen is made up of 14 members (one elected from each of the city's wards) plus a board president who is elected citywide.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The 2014 fiscal year budget topped $1 billion for the first time, a 1.9% increase over the $985.2 million budget in 2013.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis are held in odd-numbered years, with the primary elections in March and the general election in April.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The mayor is elected in odd-numbered years following the United States presidential election using a top-two approval voting primary.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The aldermen representing odd-numbered wards are up for election at the same time as the mayor.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The president of the board of aldermen and the aldermen from even-numbered wards are elected in the off-years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city has not had a Republican mayor since 1949, and the last time a Republican was elected to another citywide office was in the 1970s.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] As of 2015, all 28 of the city's aldermen are Democrats.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Forty-eight individuals have held the office of mayor of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, four of whom—William Carr Lane, John Fletcher Darby, John Wimer, and John How—served non-consecutive terms.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The most terms served by a mayor was by Lane, who served 8 full terms plus the unexpired term of Darby.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The current mayor is Cara Spencer, who took office on April 15, 2025.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] She is the city's third consecutive female mayor.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Her predecessor Tishaura Jones who took office April 20, 2021, was the first African-American woman to hold the post.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Jones succeeded Lyda Krewson, the first female mayor of the city, who retired in 2021 after serving for four years.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The longest-serving mayor was Francis Slay, who took office April 17, 2001, and left office April 18, 2017, a total of 16 years and six days over four terms in office.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The shortest-serving mayor was Arthur Barret, who died 11 days after taking office.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis County in 1876, some mechanisms have been put in place for joint funding management and funding of regional assets.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Zoo-Museum district collects property taxes from residents of both St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis City and County, and the funds are used to support cultural institutions including the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Art Museum and the Missouri Botanical Gardens.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Similarly, the Metropolitan Sewer District provides sanitary and storm sewer service to the city and much of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Bi-State Development Agency (now known as Metro) runs the region's MetroLink light rail system and bus system.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Sheriff's Office (STLSO or STLCSO) primarily provides security services for the courtrooms, and serves court documents and issues gun carry permits.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In 2022, it gained the ability to make arrests and traffic stops.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Formed in 1876, the Sheriff's Office has over 200 employees, of which 165 are deputies.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is split between 8 districts in the Missouri House of Representatives: the 76th, 77th, 78th, 79th, 80th, 81st, 82nd, and 84th districts.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The 5th Missouri Senate district is entirely within the city, while the 4th is shared with St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is the heart of Missouri's 1st congressional district, which also includes part of northern St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] A Republican has not represented a significant portion of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city shifted from Republican voting to a Democratic stronghold at the presidential level since 1928.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Bush in 1988 was the most recent Republican to win even a quarter of the city's votes in a presidential election.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit and the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Missouri are based in the Thomas F.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Eagleton United States Courthouse in downtown St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is also home to a Federal Reserve System branch, the Federal Reserve Bank of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA) also maintains major facilities in the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city is home to three national research universities, Washington University in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, Saint Louis University, and the University of Missouri-St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, as classified under the Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Washington University School of Medicine in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis has been ranked among the top 10 medical schools in the country by *U.S.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] News & World Report* for as long as the list has been published, and as high as second, in 2003 and 2004.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] News & World Report* also ranks the undergraduate school and other graduate schools, such as the Washington University School of Law, in the top 20 in the nation.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Metropolitan Region is home to St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In addition to Catholic theological institutions such as Kenrick-Glennon Seminary and Aquinas Institute of Theology sponsored by the Order of Preachers, St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis is home to three Protestant seminaries: Eden Theological Seminary of the United Church of Christ, Covenant Theological Seminary of the Presbyterian Church in America, and Concordia Seminary of the St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis-based Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Public Schools (SLPS), which covers the entire city, operates more than 75 schools, attended by more than 25,000 students, including several magnet schools.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Since 2017, SLPS operates under full accreditation from the state of Missouri, having previously lost its accreditation in 2007.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The Board of Education of the city of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Since 2000, charter schools have operated in the city of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis using authorization from Missouri state law.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] These schools are sponsored by local institutions or corporations and take in students from kindergarten through high school.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] In addition, several private schools exist in the city, and the Archdiocese of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis operates dozens of parochial schools in the city, including parochial high schools.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The city also has several private high schools, including secular, Montessori, Catholic and Lutheran schools.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis University High School – a Jesuit preparatory high school founded in 1818 – is the oldest secondary educational institution in the U.S. west of the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The state-operated K-12 boarding school Missouri School for the Blind is in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis commands the 24th-largest media market in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] All of the major U.S. television networks have affiliates in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, including KTVI 2 (Fox), KMOV 4 (CBS, with MyNetworkTV on channel 32.1), KSDK 5 (NBC), KETC 9 (PBS), KPLR-TV 11 (The CW), KNLC 24 (MeTV), KDNL 30 (ABC), WRBU 46 (Ion), and WPXS 51 Daystar Television Network.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Among the area's most popular radio stations are KMOX (AM sports and talk, notable as the longtime flagship station for St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Cardinals broadcasts), KLOU (FM oldies), WIL-FM (FM country), WARH (FM adult hits), and KSLZ (FM Top 40 mainstream).
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis also supports public radio's KWMU, an NPR affiliate.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] All-sports stations, such as KFNS 590 AM "The Fan" and WXOS "101.1 ESPN" are also popular.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] KSHE 95 FM "Real Rock Radio" has broadcast rock music since November 1967 - longer than any other radio station in the United States.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Post-Dispatch* is the region's major newspaper.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Others in the region include *Ladue News*, *West Newsmagazine*, the *Webster-Kirkwood Times,* and the *Call Newspapers* which all serve parts of St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Three weeklies serve the African-American community: the *St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Magazine*, a monthly magazine, covers topics such as local history, cuisine, and lifestyles, while the weekly *St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Business Journal* provides coverage of regional business news.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis was served by an online newspaper, the *St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis Beacon*, but that publication merged with KWMU in 2013.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The primary alternative newspaper was the *Riverfront Times* before it was closed in 2024.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Many books and movies have been written about St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] A few of the most influential and prominent films are *Meet Me in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis* and *American Flyers*, and novels include *The Killing Dance*, *Meet Me in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis*, *The Runaway Soul*, *The Rose of Old St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis was a prime location for immigrants to move to, much of the early social work depicting immigrant life was based on St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, such as in the book *The Immigrant in St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Road, rail, ship, and air transportation modes connect the city with surrounding communities in Greater St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis, national transportation networks, and international locations.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Louis also supports a public transportation network that includes bus and light rail service.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Four interstate highways connect the city to a larger regional highway system.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Interstate 70, an east–west highway, runs from the northwest corner of the city to downtown St.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] The north–south Interstate 55 enters the city at the south near the Carondelet neighborhood and runs toward the center of the city, and both Interstate 64 and Interstate 44 enter the city on the west, running parallel to the east.
[src:charles-w-schwartz/st-louis-p02] Two of the four interstates (Interstates 55 and 64) merge south of Gateway Arch National Park and leave the city on the Poplar Street Bridge into Illinois, while Interstate 44 terminates at Interstate 70 at its new interchange near N Broadway and Cass Ave.
